 1183–5 June 1249","1183–1249":"1183–1249","1165–1245":"1165–1245","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1158–1234":"1158–1234","ABT 1183":"about 1183","5 JUN 1249":"5 June 1249","1249":"1249","1158":"1158","1234":"1234","1245":"1245","15 MAY 1245":"15 May 1245","1165":"1165","1252":"1252","1195":"1195","1183":"1183","Angoulême, Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Angoulême, Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France","Lusignan, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Lusignan, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France","Angoulême, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Angoulême, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Lusignan,86139,Vienne,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Damiette,,,Gouvernorat de Damiette,ÉGYPTE,":"Egypt","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"LUSIGNAN","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Andre, Francois, Lucien, Marcel.","French: habitational name from Lusignan, a place in Vienne. This surname is very rare in France. Compare   Zeno  .","History: Jean Miel (or Amiel) <i>dit</i> Lusignan from Lusignan in Vienne, France, married Marie-Thérèse Latouche in Boucherville, QC, in 1699. — A French family called <i>(de) Lusignan</i> became enormously powerful in the eastern Mediterranean during the Middle Ages. Guy de Lusignan (1129–94) was king of Cyprus from 1192 to 1194 (and before that, by right of marriage, king of the crusader state of Jerusalem). Hugues de Lusignan was king of Cyprus from 1267 to 1284 and king of Jerusalem from 1268 to 1284. During the 14th century, Lusignans became kings of the Armenian kingdom of Cilicia (on the Mediterranean coast of what is now Turkey, facing Cyprus)."],"variants":[{"name":"Zeno","meanings":["Italian (mainly southern Italy), Hispanic (mainly Puerto Rico), and African American: from the personal name <i>Zeno</i>, classical Greek <i>Zēnōn</i>, a derivative of <i>Zeus</i>, the name of the king of the gods in Greek mythology. <i>Zeno</i> or <i>Zenone</i> is the name of a 4th-century Italian saint from Verona. As an African American name it was probably adopted in honor of the Stoic philosopher Zeno of Kition.","Altered form of French   Lusignan  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugues","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hugues Capet  (  ?938–96 ) was ruler of France (  987–96 ) and founder of the Capetian dynasty.  See  <b>Hugh</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugues X de LUSIGNAN was born about 1183, in Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France as the son of Mathilde D Angouleme. He had at least 1 son with Delcia Hastings. He died on 5 June 1249, in Egypt, at the age of 67, and was buried in Angoulême, Charente, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France."},"et":{"ABT 1183–5 JUN 1249":"umbes 1183–5. juuni 1249","1183–1249":"1183–1249","1165–1245":"1165–1245","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1158–1234":"1158–1234","ABT 1183":"umbes 1183","5 JUN 1249":"5. juuni 1249","1249":"1249","1158":"1158","1234":"1234","1245":"1245","15 MAY 1245":"15. mai 1245","1165":"1165","1252":"1252","1195":"1195","1183":"1183","Angoulême, Charente, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Angoulême, Charente, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa","Lusignan, Vienne, Poitou-Ch